 &lt;span class="dark:text-neutral-300">This is a 3-part series exploring how to architect Go applications for testability using a clean architecture approach with fake implementations instead of traditional mocks.&lt;/span>
&lt;/div>

&lt;h2 id="series-overview" class="relative group">Series Overview &lt;span class="absolute top-0 w-6 transition-opacity opacity-0 -start-6 not-prose group-hover:opacity-100">&lt;a class="group-hover:text-primary-300 dark:group-hover:text-neutral-700" style="text-decoration-line: none !important;" href="#series-overview" aria-label="Anchor">#&lt;/a>&lt;/span>&lt;/h2>&lt;p>Testing difficulties are often symptoms of underlying architectural issues. When an application has clear separation of concerns and well-defined boundaries, testing becomes simpler and more effective. This series explores a pragmatic architectural approach for Go applications that makes testing straightforward through the use of &amp;ldquo;fake&amp;rdquo; implementations.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>The Art of Meaningful Commit Messages</title><link>https://nichecode.github.io/posts/the-art-of-commit-messages/</link><pubDate>Wed, 09 Apr 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://nichecode.github.io/posts/the-art-of-commit-messages/</guid><description>&lt;div class="flex rounded-md bg-primary-100 px-4 py-3 dark:bg-primary-900">
